---
import Layout from '../../../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Neighbors from "../../../../components/Neighbors.astro";
import PrevNext from "../../../../components/PrevNext.astro";
---

<Layout title="The Construction Gap — Temporal Compression" favicon="🎞️">
  <main>
    <a href="/reading/temporal-compression/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">
      ← back to temporal compression
    </a>

    <h1>The Construction Gap</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">
      Chapter 7 · 27 hypotheses, one construction, one gap
    </p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">
        Star + tree gives exactly 2n-3 edges and works 99.8% of the time.
        The remaining 0.2% always have a non-star 2n-3 spanner.
        The conjecture is empirically confirmed through n=12.
        The proof gap is one lemma wide.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2>The construction</h2>

    <p>
      Pick a hub vertex. Connect it to all n-1 others (star). Connect the
      remaining n-1 vertices in a spanning tree (n-2 edges). Total: 2n-3. Check
      temporal reachability — if every pair can reach every other pair through
      time-respecting paths using only these edges, done.
    </p>

    <p>
      For 99.8% of random temporal cliques (tested through n=20), some hub works.
      The 0.2% where no hub works still have a 2n-3 spanner — just not star-shaped.
      Multi-start greedy with backward pruning always finds one.
    </p>

    <h2>Where the log factor was</h2>

    <p>
      The <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1810.00104">CPS fireworks algorithm</a>
      proves O(n log n). The log factor comes from layered delegation: halving
      emitters each round, log(k) rounds, O(n) per round. The per-round cost
      scales with remaining emitters, but each elimination generates ~log(k)
      missed-collector edges.
    </p>

    <p>
      The source of the log(k): CPS eliminates k/2 emitters simultaneously,
      and multiple eliminated emitters miss the same collector independently.
      The overcounting is ~2x per round across log(k) rounds.
    </p>

    <p>
      Sequential delegation avoids this. Eliminate emitters one at a time.
      Each collector is missed exactly once (telescoping). Total missed = |&cup;N|,
      regardless of ordering. Empirically: |&cup;N|/k &rarr; 0.865. Total biclique
      cost &asymp; 1.865k. Within budget.
    </p>

    <h2>The proof tree</h2>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 mb-6" style="font-family: ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: 0.85em; line-height: 1.6;">
      <pre style="margin:0; white-space:pre-wrap;">spanner &le; 2n-3
├── dismount (Carnevale et al. 2025) ✓
├── biclique characterization (Thm 3.10) ✓
├── connected pair exists ← Lean, zero sorry ✓
├── budget arithmetic ← proved (omega) ✓
└── biclique spanner &le; 4k-3 ← <span style="color:#facc15;">OPEN</span>
    ├── star+tree: works 99.8% ✓
    └── non-star fallback: exists empirically, no proof</pre>
    </div>

    <p>
      The gap is one lemma: show that every non-dismountable biclique with
      extremal matchings has a temporal spanner with &le; 4k-3 cross edges.
      Star+tree nearly closes it. The 0.2% need either a non-star construction
      whose budget can be proved, or a non-constructive existence argument.
    </p>

    <h2>What doesn't work (27 hypotheses)</h2>

    <p>
      They died for four structural reasons.
    </p>

    <h3>Asymmetry kills</h3>
    <p>
      Temporal reachability is forward-transitive but backward-non-transitive.
      Union-find, Farey trees, spanning trees, BGP-style route composition,
      and symmetric data structures all died here. Six hypotheses.
    </p>

    <h3>Non-locality kills</h3>
    <p>
      An edge's relay value depends on global timestamp structure.
      No local heuristic predicts which edges are critical. Per-node rules,
      column degree, timestamp spread, Farey mediants: all structurally
      insufficient. Five hypotheses.
    </p>

    <h3>Overcorrelation kills</h3>
    <p>
      Relay sets overlap completely. One edge relays &Theta;(k&sup2;) pairs.
      Double counting, covering, and probabilistic methods die because relay
      capacity is too concentrated. Random subgraphs with 4k-3 edges are
      almost never spanners. Four hypotheses.
    </p>

    <h3>Algebraic structure kills</h3>
    <p>
      The tropical semiring lacks additive inverses. Rank-nullity fails.
      Spectral methods, lifted-ring factor rank, and LGV determinants
      compute the right object but can't bound it. Three hypotheses.
    </p>

    <h2>What does work</h2>

    <p>
      Best-response dynamics converge in 2 rounds to a near-optimal spanner
      (Price of Anarchy &le; 1.25). First distributed temporal spanner
      construction — the literature has none. Construction cost O(k&sup5;).
    </p>

    <p>
      Sequential delegation on the CPS residual biclique gives O(n) total
      spanner edges. The log factor in CPS was overcounting from parallel
      elimination.
    </p>

    <p>
      Star+tree on K<sub>n</sub> gives exactly 2n-3 edges and works on
      99.8% of instances.
    </p>

    <h2>The negative mold</h2>

    <p>
      After 27 dead ends, the proof must be:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>Combinatorial (algebraic structure is too weak)</li>
      <li>Constructive or near-constructive (random can't find the spanner)</li>
      <li>Global (local heuristics have zero predictive power)</li>
      <li>Asymmetric (must respect forward-but-not-backward transitivity)</li>
      <li>Specific to dismountability (bespoke, not off-the-shelf)</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      The <a href="https://github.com/kimjune01/june.kim/blob/master/src/data/proof-manual.yml">proof manual</a>
      surfaces candidates. It cannot generate the bespoke construction.
    </p>

    <h2>For the next attempt</h2>

    <p>
      The gap is narrow. Star+tree handles 99.8%. The 0.2% where no hub
      works have a specific structure: no vertex's temporal position is
      "central" enough to relay all pairs. These instances exist but are
      rare and get rarer with n.
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        Show every K<sub>n</sub> has a hub vertex whose star+tree is a valid
        spanner. This is false (0.2% counterexamples). But showing the
        failure rate → 0 as n → &infin; would give an asymptotic result.
      </li>
      <li>
        For the hub-less instances, construct a non-star 2n-3 spanner
        whose correctness can be proved. Multi-start greedy always finds
        one — the question is proving it.
      </li>
      <li>
        A non-constructive argument. The birthday bound suggests
        P(no hub works) &asymp; (1-p)<sup>n</sup> for some p > 0, which
        vanishes exponentially. But the conjecture needs certainty, not probability.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p>
      The construction is trivial. The proof isn't. The gap is one lemma wide.
    </p>

    <PrevNext
      prev={{ href: "/reading/temporal-compression/ch-06/", title: "← The Rosetta Stone" }}
    />
  </main>
</Layout>
